@node "req" "System requirments"
@next "files"
@prev "legal"

To use this program you will need:
·An Amiga (Unless you feel like porting the code...)
·A TI-85 calculator 
·The $4 Serial cable (Plans included or at www.ticalc.org)
·ixemul.library

Optionally you may want:
·A voltmeter to test the link cable with LinkTest
·A Preferences supported printer that can print 128 or more columns in
 Fine pitch for prtscrn

@endnode

@node "files" "Included Files"
@next "use"
@prev "req"
Files included:
---------------
send85 - Program to send variables to calculator
recv85 - Program to receive variables from calculator
ResetLink - Sets Link cable so calc doesn't slow down
prtscrn - Prints calculator screen on printer using X's
test/linktest - Tests link outputs
test/recvtest - Shows received bytes
src/#? - Source code if you want to recompile it
alink.guide - You're reading it
$4SerLink.iff - Diagram of link cable.

@endnode

@node "use" "What to do"
@next "links"
@prev "files"

First turn off the Amiga and attach the $4 serial cable between the
calculator and the amiga's internal serial port.  Serial cards cannot be
used.

If the calculator is going slow run ResetLink to correct that.

To send a variable or backup (#?.85? file) put the calculator in receive
mode and type send85 Var1 [Var2 ... ].

To receive a variable or backup just run recv85 and start the send on
the calculator.

To print the calculators screen turn on your printer and run prtscrn.
The calculator will only respond when it is not busy.  Therefore you
cannot print the screen while a program is running, or while in an
assembly shell or program.  The printer must be able to print atleast
128 columns across in Fine pitch for this to work.  The calculator
display is printed with X's on the printer.

IF THE LINK DOESN'T SEEM TO WORK ON FASTER AMIGAS you may havce to add a
delay.  This is done by creating the ALINK_DELAY environment variable
(env:ALINK_DELAY).  Put a decimal number in it.  Th ehigher the number
the slower the programs go.  No delay is needed for my A3000/030/25, but
the A1200/030/40 needs a value somewhere around 50.  Try experimenting
with it using the set command between tries.  When you find the right
value put it in ENVARC:ALINK_DELAY so it will always be set.

@endnode

@node "links" "Link Cable"
@next "comp"
@prev "use"

See the enclosed picture for how to build it or check www.ticalc.org for
more info.

To test the cable use the test/LinkTest program.  Before runningn it
attach the negative (black) lead of a voltmeter to the base of he plug.


   RING
|   |
|______
|  | | >
|------
| |   |
  |  TIP
  |
Voltmeters 
-ve (Black) lead

After running Linktest touch the other lead to the other contacts to
check if they match what LinkTest says they should be.

HIGH should be around 4.7V or close to the value of the zener diodes
used.  LOW should be about -.7V.

To really test the link attach it to the calculator and run RecvTest.
try sending xStat.  You should see something like this:

7.ADE:home/ALink> recvtest
85              <- Calculator ID 85 = TI85 05=computer 

6               <-Other info, check files at www.ticalc.org if you care
9  
0  
2  
0  
4  
5               <-Name Length
78  x           <-Variable name
53  S
74  t
61  a
74  t
1f              <-Packet checksum
2  
^C

If you see garbage here you may have a problem with the cable or you may
need to add some delay if you have a faster amiga (See @{"Usage" link
"use"}).


7.ADE:home/ALink> _

@endnode

@node "comp" "Compilation"
@next "history"
@prev "links"

This program was written with gcc 2.7.2 from the current version at
ftp.ninemoons.com.  It was compiled with the -O2 -m68000 options.  It
does work with libnix if you don't want ixemul, but break check doens't
seem to work very well.  

To compile just do a 'make all' form inside the src directory.

files:
------
tiport.c - Serial port access and sending and receiving of bytes
tiportp.c - Experimental Parallel port link stuff.  Doesn't work.
packet.c - Sending and receiving packets
send85.c      \
recv85.c       \
ResetLink.c     \___The actual 
prtscrn.c       /   programs
linktest.c     /
recvtest.c    /
version.h - version info


@endnode

@node "history" "The Past"
@next "bugs"
@prev "comp"
ver 0.9 (???)
	-First working version
ver 1.0 (May 21, 1997)
	-0.9 worked fine with files received by it, but not true #?.85? 
	 files because I forgot about word ordering.  Two days later I 
	 got it all.  I hope :-)
	-Wrote prtscrn just to see if I could do it.
	-Added timeout routines to tiport.c
ver 1.1 (Aug 7, 1997) (Unreleased)
	-Learned about resources, so now the OS knows the serial port is
	 being messed with.
	-Got the timeout working right.  Gotta get some real ANSI C docs...
	-Fixed some typos in the code
	-Corrected the version string.
	-Changed link diagram from gif to iff format and adjusted it for 
	 a 25pin serial port.
ver 1.2 (Aug 30, 1997)
	-Updated my GCC to latest current GG version
	-Added delay to work on faster machines
	-Added ResetLink
	-Removed debug info to shrink executables
	-Removed TIDocs to save space.  They are available from
         www.ticalc.org
	-Wrote AmigaGuide docs
@endnode

@node "bugs" "The Present"
@next "todo"
@prev "history"

·No GUI.  I am not that good a programer, and don't know much past straight
 ANSI C.  
·According to the origional source the resend on a bad checksum doesn't
 work.  I haven't been able to test this.
·More link cables need to be supported!
   I know of at least these ones:
	·$4 serial link			(Supported)
	·$5 parallel link               
	·TI Link85 cable (Old black one)
	·TI GraphLink cable (Grey one)
	·CONNECT 85 cable
·The code is very messy...

@endnode

